SIMPLE: heathen
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Heathen
<hw>Hea"then</hw> <pr>(h⟦emac⟧"⟦th⟧'n; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Heathens</plw> <pr>(-⟦th⟧'nz)</pr> or
<xex>collectively</xex> <plw>Heathen</plw>.</plu> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hethen</ets>, AS. <ets>h⟦aemac⟧⟦edh⟧en</ets>, prop. an adj. fr.
<ets>h⟦aemac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets> heath, and orig., therefore, one who lives in
the country or on the heaths and in the woods (cf. <ets>pagan</ets>, fr.
<ets>pagus</ets> village); akin to OS. <ets>h⟦emac⟧⟦edh⟧in</ets>, adj.,
D. <ets>heiden</ets> a heathen, G. <ets>heide</ets>, OHG.
<ets>heidan</ets>, Icel. <ets>hei⟦edh⟧inn</ets>, adj., Sw.
<ets>heden</ets>, Goth. <ets>hai⟦thorn⟧n⟦omac⟧</ets>, <pos>n.</pos> fem.
See <er>Heath</er>, and cf. <er>Hoiden</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An
individual of the pagan or unbelieving nations, or those which worship
idols and do not acknowledge the true God; a pagan; an
idolater.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An irreligious person.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If it is no more than a moral discourse, he may preach it and they
may hear it, and yet both continue unconverted <qex>heathens</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>V. Knox.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The heathen</b></col>, <cd>as the term is used in the
Scriptures, all people except the Jews; now used of all people except
Christians, Jews, and Muslims.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ask of me, and I shall give thee the <qex>heathen</qex> for thine
inheritance.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. ii. 8.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Pagan; gentile. See <er>Pagan</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heathen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Heathen
<hw>Hea"then</hw> <pr>(h⟦emac⟧"⟦th⟧'n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Gentile; pagan; <as>as, a <ex>heathen</ex> author</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>heathen</xex> philosopher.⟦rdquo⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧All in gold,
like <xex>heathen</xex> gods.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Barbarous; unenlightened; heathenish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Irreligious; scoffing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heathendom</ent>⟦br⟧
